# Read Agent Model from YAML Frontmatter Instead of Hardcoding

## Context
Each agent file in .claude/agents/*.md has YAML frontmatter with a model field:
```yaml
---
name: drummer
description: BEAT — syncopation-obsessed drummer
model: sonnet
---
```

But agent-process-manager.ts hardcodes '--model', 'haiku' at line 178 in spawnAgent(). The YAML frontmatter model value is completely ignored — buildAgentSystemPrompt() strips it at line 230.

## Why This Change
Making the .md files the source of truth for model selection:
1. Enables per-agent model selection (e.g., melody on sonnet for better harmonic reasoning, drums on haiku for speed)
2. Eliminates the mismatch between documented and actual model
3. Makes it easy to experiment with different models per agent

## What to Change

### 1. Parse Model from Frontmatter
In buildAgentSystemPrompt(), instead of just stripping frontmatter, also extract the model field. Change the method to return both the system prompt and the model:

```typescript
private buildAgentSystemPrompt(agentKey: string): { prompt: string; model: string } | null {
  const agentFile = AGENT_KEY_TO_FILE[agentKey];
  if (!agentFile) return null;

  const filePath = path.join(this.workingDir, '.claude', 'agents', `${agentFile}.md`);
  try {
    const content = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf-8');
    // Extract model from YAML frontmatter
    const frontmatterMatch = content.match(/^---\n([\s\S]*?)\n---/);
    let model = 'haiku'; // default fallback
    if (frontmatterMatch) {
      const modelMatch = frontmatterMatch[1].match(/model:\s*(\S+)/);
      if (modelMatch) model = modelMatch[1];
    }
    // Strip frontmatter for system prompt
    const body = content.replace(/^---[\s\S]*?---\n*/, '');
    return { prompt: body, model };
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(`[AgentManager] Failed to read agent file: ${filePath}`, err);
    return null;
  }
}
```

### 2. Use Extracted Model in spawnAgent()
Update spawnAgent() to use the model from the return value:
```typescript
private async spawnAgent(key: string): Promise<void> {
  const result = this.buildAgentSystemPrompt(key);
  if (!result) { ... }
  const { prompt: systemPrompt, model } = result;

  const proc = spawn('claude', [
    '--print',
    '--verbose',
    '--model', model,  // from frontmatter, not hardcoded
    // ... rest unchanged
    '--system-prompt', systemPrompt,
    // ...
  ]);
}
```

### 3. Update Agent Files
Update all 4 .md files to reflect the intended model. Current value is 'sonnet' but agents run on 'haiku'. Decide which model each agent should use and set accordingly. If keeping haiku for all, change to model: haiku.

## Files
- lib/agent-process-manager.ts (main logic)
- .claude/agents/drummer.md (update model value)
- .claude/agents/bassist.md (update model value)
- .claude/agents/melody.md (update model value)
- .claude/agents/fx-artist.md (update model value)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Model is read from YAML frontmatter in each .md file
- Falls back to 'haiku' if no model field exists
- spawnAgent() uses the extracted model instead of hardcoded 'haiku'
- All 4 .md files have correct model values
- Console log shows which model each agent is using
- No TypeScript compilation errors

# Add Autonomous Tick System for Organic Jam Evolution

## Context
In the current architecture, agents ONLY produce new patterns when the boss sends a directive via handleDirective(). After sendJamStart() creates the opening patterns, the jam is frozen until the human intervenes. This contradicts the vision of organic, self-evolving jams.

## Why This Change
For jams to evolve autonomously:
1. Agents need periodic updates showing what the band is currently playing
2. They need the opportunity to respond (or hold steady with "no_change")
3. The jam should develop a life of its own, with the boss as an optional guide

## Dependencies
- cc_sick_beats-wfb (no_change sentinel): Agents need to be able to say "no_change" during ticks, otherwise every tick forces a pattern change
- cc_sick_beats-pyk (round number): Ticks should increment the round counter for arc guidance

## What to Change

### 1. Add Tick Timer to AgentProcessManager
In lib/agent-process-manager.ts:

Add a private field:
```typescript
private tickTimer: NodeJS.Timeout | null = null;
private roundNumber = 0;
```

In start(), after sendJamStart():
```typescript
this.startAutoTick();
```

New method:
```typescript
private startAutoTick(): void {
  this.tickTimer = setInterval(() => {
    if (this.stopped) return;
    this.sendAutoTick();
  }, 30000); // 30 seconds
}
```

### 2. Build Auto-Tick Context
New method sendAutoTick() — similar to sendJamStart() but framed differently:
```typescript
private async sendAutoTick(): Promise<void> {
  this.roundNumber++;
  const ctx = this.musicalContext;

  const responsePromises = this.activeAgents.map((key) => {
    if (!this.agents.has(key)) return Promise.resolve(null);

    const bandStateLines = this.activeAgents
      .filter((k) => k !== key)
      .map((k) => {
        const meta = AGENT_META[k];
        const pattern = this.agentPatterns[k] || 'silence';
        return `${meta.emoji} ${meta.name} (${k}): ${pattern}`;
      });

    const context = [
      `TICK — Round ${this.roundNumber}`,
      `Key: ${ctx.key} | Scale: ${ctx.scale.join(', ')} | BPM: ${ctx.bpm} | Energy: ${ctx.energy}/10`,
      '',
      'BAND STATE:',
      ...bandStateLines,
      '',
      `Your current pattern: ${this.agentPatterns[key] || 'silence'}`,
      '',
      'Listen to the band. If the music calls for a change, evolve your pattern.',
      'If your current groove serves the song, respond with "no_change".',
      'Stability is a musical choice.',
    ].join('\n');

    this.setAgentStatus(key, 'thinking');
    return this.sendToAgentAndCollect(key, context);
  });

  const responses = await Promise.all(responsePromises);
  for (let i = 0; i < this.activeAgents.length; i++) {
    this.applyAgentResponse(this.activeAgents[i], responses[i]);
  }
  this.composeAndBroadcast();
}
```

### 3. Reset Timer on Boss Directive
In handleDirective(), reset the tick timer to avoid double-triggering:
```typescript
if (this.tickTimer) {
  clearInterval(this.tickTimer);
}
this.roundNumber++;
// ... existing directive logic ...
this.startAutoTick(); // Restart timer after directive
```

### 4. Clean Up on Stop
In stop():
```typescript
if (this.tickTimer) {
  clearInterval(this.tickTimer);
  this.tickTimer = null;
}
```

### 5. Consider Staggering (optional enhancement)
Instead of ticking all agents simultaneously, consider staggering:
- Tick 1 (30s): drums + bass
- Tick 2 (45s): melody + fx
This creates a more organic feel where not everyone changes at once. But this adds complexity — implement the simple version first.

## Files
- lib/agent-process-manager.ts (main changes)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Auto-tick fires every ~30 seconds during active jam sessions
- Tick context is framed as "listen and optionally evolve" (not "produce new pattern")
- Agents can respond with "no_change" (depends on cc_sick_beats-wfb)
- Round number increments on each tick and directive (depends on cc_sick_beats-pyk)
- Timer resets when boss sends a directive
- Timer clears on stop()
- No memory leaks (interval properly cleaned up)
- Jam continues to function with boss directives alongside auto-ticks
